President Muhammadu Buhari, on Monday night, ordered the total lockdown of Kano State for two weeks to check the spread of coronavirus in the state. He said in his nationwide broadcast, “With regards to Kano, I have directed the enforcement of a total lockdown for a period of two weeks effective immediately. The Federal Government shall deploy all the necessary human, material and technical resources to support the State in controlling and containing the pandemic and preventing the risk of further spread to neighboring States.” Buhari also promised to support the Kano State Government to tackle the raging pandemic. He stressed the resolve of the Federal Government to deploy all necessary machineries to enable the state to contain the pandemic. The President said, “The Federal Government shall deploy all the necessary human, material and technical resources to support the state in controlling and containing the pandemic”. While easing the lockdown imposed on Lagos, Ogun and the FCT effective from May 4, Buhari said the total lockdown in Kano will be for two weeks, starting from today. Governor Abdullahi Umar Ganduje had earlier in the day decried the alleged neglect of the state by the Federal Task Force Committee on COVID-19, despite the intensity of the situation in the state. 